## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 911](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section911) lets a U.S. citizen (or qualifying long-term resident) elect to exclude foreign earned income from gross income, up to the [§ 911(b)(2)(D)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section911) annual ceiling (Rev. Proc. 2024-40 § 3.34: **$130,000** for 2025). [§ 911(c)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section911) routes qualifying housing expenses to either a housing exclusion (employees) or a housing deduction (self-employed taxpayers, § 911(c)(4)). The election requires meeting either the bona-fide-residence test (§ 911(d)(1)(A)) or the physical-presence test (§ 911(d)(1)(B)).

Two cross-cutting consequences flow from the § 911 election:

- [**§ 911(d)(6)**](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section911) denies any FTC on foreign tax allocable to the excluded portion of foreign earned income, so excluded wages cannot also generate creditable foreign tax.
- [**§ 1411(d)(1)(A)**](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1411) adds the excluded amount back to MAGI for Net Investment Income Tax purposes, so § 911 does not also reduce the § 1411 base.

For 2025 the engine consumes the FEIE election state from the loader; when the election is not made every output is zero and the rest of the pipeline (§ 63 taxable income, § 904 FTC denominator, § 1411 NIIT) flows through unchanged.

